06009nam a22006855i 9780824839116DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024049990  a(OCoLC)1029821035  a97808248391167 a10.1515/97808248391162doi  a(DE-B1597)483865  a(OCoLC)859157614  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aLIT0080002bisacsh1 aSears, Laurie J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSituated Testimonies :bDread and Enchantment in an Indonesian Literary Archive /cLaurie J. Sears. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b10 illus., 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Conventions -- tSelected Timeline of Indies and Indonesian Histories -- tIntroduction: The Afterwardsness of History -- tChapter 1. Desire, Phantoms, and Commodities: Maria Dermoût’s Colonial Critique -- tChapter 2. At Home and Not at Home in Empire: Transnational Phantasies of Colonial Modernity -- tChapter 3. A Neurotic Family Romance of Modernity and the National Form -- tChapter 4. The End of the Nationalist Romance -- tChapter 5. Trauma and Its Doubles in Postcolonial Masculinity -- tChapter 6. Masculinist Trauma and Feminist Melancholia -- tAfterword: Trauma, Translation, and a Critical Path -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Indonesian writer Pramoedya Ananta Toer made a distinction between a “downstream” literary reality and an “upstream” historical reality. Pramoedya suggested that literature has an effect on the upstream flow of history and that it can in fact change history. In Situated Testimonies Laurie Sears illuminates this process by considering a selection of Dutch Indies and Indonesian literary works that span the twentieth century and beyond and by showing how authors like Louis Couperus and Maria Dermoût help retell and remodel history.Sears sees certain literary works as “situated testimonies,” bringing ineffable experiences of trauma into narrative form and preserving something of the dread and enchantment that animated the past. These literary works offer a method of reading the emotional traces that historians may fail to witness or record—traces that elude archival constructions where political factors or colonial conditions have influenced processes of what is preserved and how it is shaped. Sears’ use of Donna Haraway’s notion of “situatedness” reiterates the idea that all of us speak from somewhere. Testimony, especially eyewitness testimony, is a gold standard in historical methodology, and the authors of literary works are eyewitnesses of their time. But the works of authors like Tirto Adhi Soerjo and Soewarsih Djojopoespito are first of all written as literature, and literary or stylistic devices cannot be ignored.Sears finds substantial evidence of the movement of psychoanalytic theories between Europe and the Indies/Indonesia throughout the twentieth century. She concludes that far from being only a Jewish or European discourse, psychoanalysis is a transnational discourse of desire that has influenced Indies and Indonesian writers for more than a century. Psychoanalytic ideas, and the suggestion by French psychoanalyst Jean Laplanche and Indonesian author Ayu Utami that memories, like literature, can move us back and forth in time, have inspired Sears’ thinking about historical archives, literature, and trauma.Soekarno’s words haunt this book as he haunts Indonesia’s past. Situated Testimonies rewrites portions of the literary and social history of Indonesia over a sweep of many decades. Historians, scholars of literary theory, and Indonesianists will all be interested in the book’s insights on how colonial and postcolonial novels of the Indies and Indonesia illuminate nationalist narratives and imperial histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483911640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824839116423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824839116/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK